## 1. Context

The relevant block is `onQuery` in `src/mdns.js`, lines 76–92:

```js
// src/mdns.js, lines 76–92
const onQuery = (packet) => {
  if (!mdnsInstance || currentRecords.length === 0) return;

  const needsResponse = packet.questions && packet.questions.some(q => {
    return q.name === `_http._tcp.local` ||
           q.name === `${activeServiceName}._http._tcp.local` ||
           q.name === `${activeHostName}.local`;
  });

  if (needsResponse) {
    try {
      mdnsInstance.respond({ answers: currentRecords });
    } catch (e) {
      // Ignore response errors        // <-- the problem
    }
  }
};
```



---

## 2. Root Cause

There are two distinct issues layered here:

**a) The catch block is completely silent.**
Any exception thrown synchronously by `mdnsInstance.respond()` — e.g. a closed/destroyed socket, a serialization error, or a network-level failure — is caught and discarded with only a dead comment. No log, no counter, nothing. This makes diagnosing flaky mDNS behaviour in production nearly impossible.


**b) `mdnsInstance.respond()` is called without a callback here.**
Contrast this with the `announce` function (line 208) and `deregister` (line 235), which both pass a callback to `respond()` and handle the `err` argument. In `onQuery`, the callback-less form is used, so async send errors are never surfaced at all — the catch only covers synchronous throws.


---

## 3. Suggested Fix

**File:** `src/mdns.js`

**Step 1 — Replace the silent catch with a conditional log (lines 86–91):**

```js
if (needsResponse) {
  try {
    mdnsInstance.respond({ answers: currentRecords }, (err) => {
      if (err && config && config.verbose) {
        console.debug(`[filedrop:mDNS] respond() error in onQuery: ${err.message}`);
      }
    });
  } catch (e) {
    // Only reached on synchronous throws (e.g. socket already destroyed)
    if (config && config.verbose) {
      console.debug(`[filedrop:mDNS] respond() threw synchronously in onQuery: ${e.message}`);
    }
  }
}
```

**Step 2 — Thread `config` (or just the `verbose` flag) into `onQuery`.**
`onQuery` is currently a module-level arrow function with no access to `config`. The cleanest approach is to convert it to a factory:

```js
// Replace the top-level `const onQuery = ...` with a factory:
function makeOnQuery(verbose) {
  return (packet) => {
    if (!mdnsInstance || currentRecords.length === 0) return;

    const needsResponse = packet.questions && packet.questions.some(q =>
      q.name === `_http._tcp.local` ||
      q.name === `${activeServiceName}._http._tcp.local` ||
      q.name === `${activeHostName}.local`
    );

    if (needsResponse) {
      try {
        mdnsInstance.respond({ answers: currentRecords }, (err) => {
          if (err && verbose) {
            console.debug(`[filedrop:mDNS] respond() error in onQuery: ${err.message}`);
          }
        });
      } catch (e) {
        if (verbose) {
          console.debug(`[filedrop:mDNS] respond() threw in onQuery: ${e.message}`);
        }
      }
    }
  };
}
```

**Step 3 — Update the two call sites that reference `onQuery`.**

In `announce` (line 205), replace:
```js
instance.on('query', onQuery);
```
with:
```js
const onQuery = makeOnQuery(config.verbose);
instance.on('query', onQuery);
```
Store `onQuery` somewhere accessible to `deregister` (e.g. a module-level `let activeOnQuery = null`).

In `deregister` (line 238), replace:
```js
mdnsInstance.removeListener('query', onQuery);
```
with:
```js
mdnsInstance.removeListener('query', activeOnQuery);
activeOnQuery = null;
```

---

## 4. Effort

**S** — This is a self-contained change in a single ~250-line file. The logic is straightforward; the only care needed is correctly threading the listener reference through to `deregister`.

---

## 5. Prerequisites

| Concept | Why it matters here |
|---|---|
| **mDNS / DNS-SD** | Understanding PTR/SRV/TXT/A records and why a host must respond to queries to stay discoverable. |
| **`multicast-dns` API** | `respond(packet, [callback])` — the callback receives an `err`; without it, async send errors are invisible. |
| **Node.js EventEmitter** | `on` / `removeListener` require the *same function reference*; converting to a factory means you must store the returned closure to remove it later. |
| **Verbose/debug logging conventions** | The rest of the codebase gates noisy logs behind `config.verbose` (see lines 151, 170–171); the fix should follow the same pattern. |

